    "q": "{'content': 'Consider the following statements with respect to user-level threads and kernel-supported threads. \\n\ni) Context switch is faster with kernel- supported threads\\n\nii) For user-level threads, a system call can block the entire process\\n\niii) Kernel-supported threads can be scheduled independently\\n\niv) Use-level threads are transparent to the kernel\\nWhich of the above statements are true?\n ', 'options': [{'identifier': 'A', 'content': '(ii), (iii) & (iv) only '}, {'identifier': 'B', 'content': '(ii) & (iii) only '}, {'identifier': 'C', 'content': '(i) & (iii) only '}, {'identifier': 'D', 'content': '(i) & (ii) only'}], 'correct_options': ['A'], 'answer': None, 'explanation': \"Case (i): This is False.\nAs in kernal level threads to go from one thread to other thread we need to call Operating System but in user-level-threads without calling the OS we can context switch from one thread to another.  \n\nCase (ii): This is True. \n As in user-level-threads threads are created by the user, so Operating System's Kernal has no idea about how many threads are present inside a process/task.That is why when one thread get blocked entire process/task will be blocked by the OS.   \n\nCase (iii): This is True. \n As kernal supported threads are created by kernal itself,so kernal knows how many threads are present inside a process/task.That is why kernal can schedule each thread independently.  \n\nCase (iv): This is True. \nAs in user-level-threads threads are created by the user, so Operating System's kernal has no idea about how many threads are present inside a process/task.So we can say user-level-threads are transparent to the OS kernal.\"}",
