    "q": "{'content': 'An implementation of a queue Q, using two stacks S1 and S2, is given below :\\nvoid insert(Q, X){\\n  push(S1, X);\\n}\\n\\nvoid delete(Q){\\nif(stack - empty(S2)) then {\\n  if(stack - empty(S1)) then {\\n   print(\"Q is empty\");\\n   return;\\n  }else while (!(stack - empty(S1))){\\n   X = pop(S1);\\n   push(S2, X);\\n }\\n X = pop(S2);\\n}\\nLet n insert and $$m( \\\\le n)$$ delete operations be performed in an arbitrary order on an empty queue Q. Let x and y be the number of push and pop operations performed respectively in the process. Which one of the following is true for all m and n?', 'options': [{'identifier': 'A', 'content': '$$n + m \\\\le x \\\\le 2n$$ and $$2m \\\\le y \\\\le n + m$$'}, {'identifier': 'B', 'content': '$$n + m \\\\le x \\\\le 2n$$ and $$2m \\\\le y \\\\le 2n$$'}, {'identifier': 'C', 'content': '$$2m \\\\le x \\\\le 2n$$ and $$2m \\\\le y \\\\le n + m$$'}, {'identifier': 'D', 'content': '$$2m \\\\le x \\\\le 2n$$ and $$2m \\\\le y \\\\le 2n$$'}], 'correct_options': ['A'], 'answer': None, 'explanation': 'Let\\'s analyze the number of push (x) and pop (y) operations based on the provided implementation of the queue using two stacks, S1 and S2. Let n be the total number of insert operations and m be the total number of delete operations, with m <= n.\n\\nAnalysis of x (total push operations):\n\\n\\ninsert(Q, X) function:\n\\n\\npush(S1, X);\n\\nEach of the n insert operations performs exactly one push(S1, X). This contributes n to x.\n\\ndelete(Q) function (specifically the part involving push):\n\\n\\nWhen S2 is empty and S1 is not empty, elements are transferred from S1 to S2:\n\\nwhile (!(stack - empty(S1))){\\n\\n  X = pop(S1);\\n\\n  push(S2, X); // This is a push operation to S2\\n\\n}\\n\\nMaximum x: Each of the n distinct elements inserted into the queue is pushed onto S1 once. Subsequently, that same element might be moved from S1 to S2 (in which case it\\'s pushed onto S2 once). An element can be pushed to S2 at most once in its lifetime, as after it\\'s in S2, it\\'s either deleted or remains there.\n\\n\\nThus, the total number of push(S1) operations is n.\n\\nThe total number of push(S2) operations can be at most n (if all n elements are eventually transferred from S1 to S2).\n\\nTherefore, the maximum number of total push operations x is n + n = 2n.\n\\nx <= 2n.\n\\nMinimum x: There are always n push(S1) operations (one for each insert). Additionally, for each of the m successful delete operations, an element must eventually be popped from S2. To be eligible for pop(S2), that element must have been pushed onto S2 at some point. Therefore, at least m push(S2) operations are performed for the m successfully deleted elements.\n\\n\\nThus, x >= n (for S1) + m (for S2).\n\\nx >= n + m.\n\\nCombining these, we get: n + m <= x <= 2n.\n\\n\\nAnalysis of y (total pop operations):\n\\n\\ndelete(Q) function (specifically the part involving pop):\n\\n\\nThe delete operation itself performs X = pop(S2); regardless of whether a transfer occurred (unless the queue is entirely empty). There are m successful delete operations. This contributes m to y.\n\\nWhen S2 is empty and S1 is not empty, elements are transferred from S1 to S2:\n\\nwhile (!(stack - empty(S1))){\\n\\n  X = pop(S1); // This is a pop operation from S1\\n\\n  push(S2, X);\\n\\n}\\n\\nMaximum y: Each of the n distinct elements inserted into the queue can be popped from S1 at most once (because it moves to S2 and doesn\\'t return).\n\\n\\nThus, the total number of pop(S1) operations can be at most n.\n\\nThe total number of pop(S2) operations is exactly m (for m successful delete operations).\n\\nTherefore, the maximum number of total pop operations y is n + m.\n\\ny <= n + m.\n\\nMinimum y: Each of the m successfully deleted elements must have been popped from S2. Also, to be available in S2, these elements must have been transferred from S1 (as they are initially pushed to S1). This transfer implies they were popped from S1. Therefore, each of the m deleted elements contributes one pop(S1) and one pop(S2).\n\\n\\nThus, y >= m (from S1) + m (from S2).\n\\ny >= 2m.\n\\nCombining these, we get: 2m <= y <= n + m.\n\\n\\nConclusion:\n\\nBased on the analysis:\n\\n\\nFor pushes (x): n + m <= x <= 2n\n\\nFor pops (y): 2m <= y <= n + m\n\\n\\nThis matches Option A.\n\\nThe final answer is $\\\\boxed{A}$\n'}",
