    "q": "{'content': 'Consider the languages $${L_1}$$, $${L_2}$$ and $${L_3}$$ are given below.\\n$$$\\\\eqalign{\\n  & {L_1} = \\\\left\\\\{ {{0^p}{1^q}\\\\left| {p,q \\\\in N} \\\\right.} \\\\right\\\\}  \\\\cr \\n  & {L_2} = \\\\left\\\\{ {{0^p}{1^q}\\\\left| {p,q \\\\in N} \\\\right.\\\\,\\\\,and\\\\,\\\\,p = q} \\\\right\\\\}\\\\,\\\\,and  \\\\cr \\n  & {L_3} = \\\\left\\\\{ {{0^p}{1^q}{0^r}\\\\left| {p,q,r\\\\, \\\\in N\\\\,\\\\,\\\\,and\\\\,\\\\,\\\\,p = q = r} \\\\right.} \\\\right\\\\}. \\\\cr} $$$\\nWhich of the following statements is not TRUE?\n\\n', 'options': [{'identifier': 'A', 'content': 'Pushdown automata $$(PDA)$$ can be used to recognize $${L_1}$$ and $${L_2}$$'}, {'identifier': 'B', 'content': '$${L_1}$$ is a regular language '}, {'identifier': 'C', 'content': 'All the three languages are context free '}, {'identifier': 'D', 'content': 'Turing machines can be used to recognize all the languages'}], 'correct_options': ['C'], 'answer': None, 'explanation': 'Given Languages :\\n\\n$ L_1 = \\\\{ 0^p1^q \\\\mid p, q \\\\in N \\\\} $\n\\n\\n\\nStrings of any number of 0s followed by any number of 1s.\n\\n\\n\\n$ L_2 = \\\\{ 0^p1^q \\\\mid p, q \\\\in N \\\\text{ and } p = q \\\\} $\n\\n\\n\\nStrings where the number of 0s equals the number of 1s.\n\\n\\n\\n$ L_3 = \\\\{ 0^p1^q0^r \\\\mid p, q, r \\\\in N \\\\text{ and } p = q = r \\\\} $\n\\n\\n\\nStrings where the number of 0s, 1s, and 0s again are all equal.\n\\n\\n\\nAnalyzing Each Statement:\\nOption A: PDAs can be used to recognize $ L_1 $ and $ L_2 $.\\n\\n$ L_1 $:\n\n\\nRegular expression: $ 0^*1^* $\n\n\\nRegular language, hence can be recognized by a finite automaton (a PDA can also recognize it).\n\n\\n$ L_2 $:\n\n\\nLanguage of the form $ 0^n1^n $\n\n\\nContext-free language, can be recognized by a Pushdown Automaton (PDA).\n\n\\nConclusion: True\n\n\\n\\nOption B: $ L_1 $ is a regular language.\\n\\n$ L_1 $:\n\n\\nAs established, it can be represented by the regular expression $ 0^*1^* $.\n\n\\nRegular language.\n\n\\nConclusion: True\n\n\\n\\nOption C: All three languages are context-free.\\n\\n$ L_1 $: Regular (hence context-free).\n\n\\n$ L_2 $: Context-free.\n\n\\n$ L_3 $:\n\n\\nLanguage of the form $ 0^n1^n0^n $.\n\n\\nNot context-free. This is a well-known non-context-free language because context-free grammars cannot enforce equal counts of three different symbols.\n\n\\nConclusion: False\n\n\\n\\nOption D: Turing machines can be used to recognize all the languages.\\n\\nTuring Machines:\n\n\\nCapable of recognizing all recursively enumerable languages, which include regular, context-free, and some non-context-free languages.\n\n\\n$ L_3 $:\n\n\\nAlthough not context-free, $ L_3 $ is recursively enumerable.\n\n\\nConclusion: True\n\n\\n\\n\\nFinal Answer:\\n\\nOption A: True\n\n\\nOption B: True\n\n\\nOption C: False\n\n\\nOption D: True\n\n\\n\\n\\nTherefore, the statement that is not true is:\n\\nAnswer: Option C\n'}",
