    "q": "{'content': 'Consider the following decision problems :\\n\n\n$${P_1}$$ Does a given finite state machine accept a given string\\n\n\n$${P_2}$$ Does a given context free grammar generate an infinite number of stings.\\nWhich of the following statements is true?\n', 'options': [{'identifier': 'A', 'content': 'Both $${P_1}$$ and $${P_2}$$ are decidable '}, {'identifier': 'B', 'content': 'Neither $${P_1}$$ and $${P_2}$$  are decidable'}, {'identifier': 'C', 'content': 'Only $${P_1}$$ is decidable'}, {'identifier': 'D', 'content': 'Only $${P_2}$$ is decidable'}], 'correct_options': ['A'], 'answer': None, 'explanation': 'Problem P₁:\\n\"Does a given finite state machine accept a given string?\"\n\\nAnalysis of P₁:\\n\\nFinite State Machines (FSMs):\n\n\\nCan be deterministic (DFA) or nondeterministic (NFA).\n\n\\nBoth DFAs and NFAs have a finite number of states and transitions.\n\n\\n\\nDecidability:\n\n\\nDecidable Problem: A problem for which an algorithm can provide a yes/no answer for every input instance in finite time.\n\n\\n\\nAlgorithm for P₁:\n\n\\nFor DFAs:\n\\n\\nSimulate the DFA on the input string by transitioning through states according to the input symbols.\n\n\\nIf the DFA reaches an accepting state after processing the entire string, it accepts the string.\n\n\\nThe simulation takes time proportional to the length of the input string.\n\n\n\\nFor NFAs:\n\\n\\nSince NFAs can have multiple possible transitions for a given input symbol, we can:\n\n\\nUse a depth-first or breadth-first search to explore all possible paths.\n\n\\nAlternatively, convert the NFA to an equivalent DFA (subset construction), though this may increase the number of states exponentially.\n\n\\nAs both the NFA and the string are finite, the simulation will terminate.\n\n\n\\n\\nConclusion for P₁:\n\n\\nDecidable.\n\n\\nThere exists an algorithm that can determine whether the FSM accepts the given string in finite time.\n\n\\n\\n\\nProblem P₂:\\n\"Does a given context-free grammar generate an infinite number of strings?\"\n\\nAnalysis of P₂:\\n\\nContext-Free Grammars (CFGs):\n\n\\nConsist of a finite set of production rules that generate strings over some alphabet.\n\n\\nMay produce finite or infinite languages.\n\n\\n\\nDecidability:\n\n\\nDecidable Problem: Existence of an algorithm to determine whether the language generated by a CFG is infinite.\n\n\\nAlgorithm for P₂:\n\\nStep 1: Identify Generating Non-Terminals\n\n\\nUseful Symbols:\n\\n\\nNon-terminals that can derive terminal strings.\n\n\\nCompute the set of symbols that derive terminal strings using a fix-point algorithm.\n\n\\nStep 2: Build the Dependency Graph\n\n\\nDependency Graph:\n\\n\\nNodes represent non-terminals.\n\n\\nAn edge from $ A $ to $ B $ exists if $ A $ can derive a string containing $ B $.\n\n\\nStep 3: Detect Cycles Involving Useful Symbols\n\n\\nCycles:\n\\n\\nA cycle involving useful symbols indicates the possibility of generating strings of unbounded length.\n\n\\nUse graph traversal algorithms (e.g., DFS) to detect cycles.\n\n\\nStep 4: Determine Unbounded Derivations\n\n\\nIf the start symbol can reach itself through a cycle involving useful symbols, the language is infinite.\n\n\\nOtherwise, if all derivations are acyclic or cycles do not lead to increased string length, the language is finite.\n\n\\nConclusion for P₂:\n\n\\nDecidable.\n\n\\nThe algorithm terminates after finite steps and determines whether the CFG generates infinitely many strings.\n\n\\n\\n\\nFinal Conclusion:\\n\\nP₁ is decidable: We can simulate the FSM on the input string.\n\n\\nP₂ is decidable: We can analyze the CFG to determine if it generates an infinite language.\n\n\\nTherefore, both P₁ and P₂ are decidable.\n\n\\n\\n\\nAnswer: Option A\n'}",
